# ccc-node guard profile — operator-owned. Fresh root-run setup.sh installs this
# as /etc/ccc-node/guard-profile, owned by root:root, mode 0644. Use
# `setup.sh --strict-guard` to keep a fresh root install strict. Existing strict
# root nodes can opt in later with `sudo ./setup.sh --operational-relax`.
# Non-root setup never installs it, and setup never overwrites an existing file.
#
# The `operational-relax` token below makes ALL operational service/container/
# orchestrator lifecycle (systemctl/service/pm2/docker/podman/kubectl, local or
# toward any peer) and reboot-of-any-host autonomous on this node.
#
# It NEVER relaxes the catastrophic / injection set — catastrophic rm, secret
# exfiltration, protected-branch force-push/history-rewrite, DB destructive/
# migrate/replay, release/publish, repo-visibility, host power-down
# (poweroff/halt), and operator-config writes stay enforced regardless.
#
# Remove this file (or any weaker ownership) to revert the node to strict.
operational-relax

# OPTIONAL — operator-trust (operator decision 2026-07-18): uncomment on nodes
# where the sole operator wants mid-tier textual gates demoted from DENY to
# run-and-audit: non-recursive literal-path rm anywhere, and read-only
# inspection of operator config files. The catastrophic set listed above is
# enforced regardless, including operator-config WRITES — the agent can never
# loosen its own guard, trust or not.
# operator-trust
